The first is not often contemplated in public fasting, because all men have not the same constitution or health of body; therefore it is rather more applicable to private fasting. The second end is common to both, such preparation for prayer being necessary to the whole Church, as well as to every one of the faithful iu particular. The same may be said of the third. For it will sometimes happen that God will afflict a whole nation · with war, pestilence, or some other calamity; under such a common scourge, it behoves all the people to maire a confession of their guilt. When the hand of the Lord chastises an indi- vidual, he ought to make a similar confession, either alone or with his family.
